## Feature Request
Implementing `size_hint` is possible and would allow the `.collect` calls to optimize the capacity of the receiving container.

### Motivation
Free performance improvement

### Proposal
The `Iterator` trait has a method `size_hint` that library authors should implement whenever possible so that the `.collect` can pre-allocate the memory upfront and avoid multiple allocations.

```rust
impl Iterator for IntoIter {
    // Pseudo-code but should look like
    fn size_hint(&self) -> (usize, Option<usize>) {
        let first = if self.first.is_some() { 1 } else { 0 };
        let max = self.rest.size_hint().1.unwrap_or(0) + first;
        if max > 0 {
          (1, Some(max))
        } else {
          (0, Some(0))
        }
    }
}
```

Currently, none of our streamed responses allow for any kind of stream cancellation.<br><br>We should implement stream cancellation to provide more control over a given stream, as well as less resource usage for a given stream.

## Implementation

The actual implementation of this should rely on the `Abortable` type from the `futures` crate.<br><br>Below is a rough sketch of how the feature should look (this is pseudocode and doesn't need to be the exact implementation!):

```
use futures::{Stream, StreamExt, future::AbortHandle, stream::Abortable};
use async_stream::stream;
use tokio::sync::watch;

pub struct ControlledStream<T> {
    pub stream: Abortable<impl Stream<Item = Result<T, CompletionError>> + Unpin>,
    pub abort_handle: AbortHandle,
}

pub fn make_stream(
    response: reqwest::Response,
) -> ControlledStream<RawStreamingChoice> {
    let (abort_handle, abort_reg) = AbortHandle::new_pair();

    let s = stream! {
        let mut stream = response.bytes_stream();

        while let Some(chunk_result) = stream.next().await {
            // Cancel-safe
            if let Ok(chunk) = chunk_result {
                // parse lines, yield streaming responses...
                yield Ok(RawStreamingChoice::Message("...".into()));
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }
    };

    let cancelable = Abortable::new(s, abort_reg);

    ControlledStream {
        stream: cancelable,
        abort_handle,
    }
}
```

